H&P will train all rig and yard personnel on the Confined Space procedure. All personnel who may enter a confined space shall be trained in the hazards of confined space entry and in the controls required for safe entry.

Training shall include, as applicable:

- the known risks to personnel created by a confined space;
- precautions required to address those risks;
- the control measures to be used, their purpose, and how to use them;
- the use of necessary PPE;
- emergency procedures; and
- in Oman operations, understanding and application of the KCAD CSE procedure.

Any person who has a role in carrying out emergency arrangements shall receive appropriate instruction and training to enable that person to perform the role effectively. In Saudi Arabia operations, confined space rescue drills shall be performed in accordance with the Safety Drills and Exercises Procedure K-KS-HS-PR-034.

Personnel in charge of activities in the confined space shall receive adequate training and attend the Toolbox Talk. The Workgroup Leader shall lead the Toolbox Talk meeting, analyze the activities to be performed and the associated risks as per the JSA, and ensure the emergency procedure is discussed during the Toolbox Talk.

The Confined Space must be properly isolated from all energy sources. All electrical and mechanical sources of energy shall be Locked-out, Tagged-out, and Tried-out prior to entry. Isolation shall remove the space from service and, where practicable, stored energy in hydraulic, pneumatic, electrical, chemical, mechanical, thermal, and other systems shall be reduced to zero before entry is authorized.

Required isolations shall be identified in the JSA and/or risk assessment and on the permit to work, including the type of isolation to be applied, such as LOTO, double block and bleed, spades, or blind flanges (positive isolation). Isolation shall be performed by a competent, duly authorized mechanical or electrical person under a dedicated work permit and verified by the Workgroup Leader. In Saudi Arabia operations, isolations shall be achieved in accordance with the Isolations requirements in Work Permit System Procedure K-KS-HS-PR-008. In Oman operations following KCAD-Land-LOTO-001, electrical sources shall preferably be locked out at disconnect switches remote from the equipment. For Oman onshore rig mud tank or other confined area entries, a Toolbox Talk must be held before the job and documented on the permit; electrical operations and equipment must be isolated by a Senior Electrician, and mechanical operations and equipment must be isolated by a Derrick man or Assistant Driller.

Acceptable isolation methods include:
- physical disconnection;
- removal of a valve, spool piece, or expansion joint in piping leading to, and as close as possible to, the confined space, followed by blanking or capping the open end of the piping leading to the confined space;
- insertion of a suitable full-pressure spade (blank) in piping between the flanges nearest to the confined space;
- blanking and bleeding, and securing valves, cargo, ballast, pneumatic, and hydraulic lines;
- disconnecting mechanical linkages on shaft-driven equipment where possible;
- preventing movement of any confined space that can itself move, and securing agitators, fans, and other moving parts by an approved means or an alternative method offering equivalent security, including latches, chains, chocks, blocks, or other devices.

Where caps, blanks, or spades are installed, the cap or blank shall be identified to indicate its purpose and the spade shall also be identified. All isolated valves shall be tagged. In Oman mud-system work, all electrical switches for agitators must be locked out with pad locks.

In Saudi Arabia operations, where physical disconnection, removal/blanking, or spading is not practicable, local procedure permits isolation by closing and locking, or closing and tagging, or both, of at least two valves in the pipe leading to the confined space. This regional allowance does not replace the global H&P requirement that electrical and mechanical sources be Locked-out, Tagged-out, and Tried-out prior to entry.

Before entry is permitted, the following pre-entry isolation checks shall be completed where applicable:
- if dangerous machines or electrical currents are present, all potential machines in the area shall be switched off and secured under LOTO;
- dangerous surfaces shall be covered or removed, including sharp corners and hot surfaces;
- electrical devices shall not be used in metal environments unless protection is provided in a different way;
- when mud pumps are running, nobody is allowed to enter or work in a tank into which the mud pump relief lines run;
- before entry into tanks, personnel shall have at the work site a copy of the Cold Work Permit / Entry Certificate and a copy of the Standby man Instructions.

Isolation records shall be maintained with the permit package. Where the land drilling form section 2B is triggered by a "Yes" at 2A, the PIC (TP / NTP) shall complete:
- reason for entry or isolation;
- Prep/Isolation permit No.;
- mechanical isolation details;
- electrical isolation details.

Where the Electrical / Mechanical / Instrument / Operation Isolation checklist is used, the original and copy shall be with the Permit to Work and shall record:
- Rig;
- Location;
- Refers to Permit to Work No.;
- for each electrical isolation: Equipment, Isolated Date, Isolated Time, Lock or Lockout Sign No., De-Isolated Date, and De-Isolated Time;
- for each mechanical isolation: Equipment, Isolated Date, Isolated Time, Lock or Lockout Sign No., De-Isolated Date, and De-Isolated Time;
- Remarks;
- Signatures and dates for the Applicant / Job Site Leader and the Toolpusher.

**7.5.** Potential hazards and the precautions necessary to perform the work safely shall be checked on the Permit and, where required, supplemented by the confined space entry certificate/checklist. The permit package shall identify the rig/location name, date and time, PTW reference number, name, work location, and description of work, and shall record whether electrical work is involved, whether a preparation/isolation permit is required, whether confined space entry is required, and whether any additional PTW such as Hot Work is required. Before entry, all controls identified in the JSA and/or risk assessment and in the entry plan shall be in place. No confined space entry job will be allowed without use of the applicable safety tools in developing and executing the entry plan, including the permit to work, TRIC, JSA, and confined space entry checklist. The permit process shall ensure personnel are aware of all hazards involved, including for tank entry.

Each confined space shall be assessed individually because design, floor plan, internal pipework, agitator location, and similar features vary. A JSA and/or risk assessment shall identify the relevant hazards, establish the safe system of work, evaluate the risks, and confirm that entry will not be undertaken if the risk is unacceptable. Hazards to be considered and safeguarded against shall include:

- oxygen deficiency or oxygen enrichment/excess, including a verified oxygen concentration between 19.5% and 23.5%; no entry is permitted outside this range;
- fire and explosion;
- chemical or toxic substances; toxicity information for specific substances shall be obtained from suppliers, normally via SDS / Saudi Aramco CHB, and shall be available on site;
- electric shock;
- dust and particulates;
- inadequate lighting level/illumination;
- slip, trip, and fall hazards;
- poor condition of ladders or inadequate fall protection for access/exit of the confined space;
- internal pipework, the potential for ingress of fluid, and machinery requiring isolation, such as mud pit agitator blades;
- the potential for gas release from mud sediment;
- static electricity generated by steam jetting, water jetting, or grit blasting;
- simultaneous operations (SIMOPS); and
- the possibility that the space can fill with liquid.

Precautions checked on the Permit shall, as applicable, include:

- personnel entering the space have been trained on confined space entry hazards;
- a designated trained standby person/man is assigned, is aware of all duties, remains at the area, and does not leave unless relieved by a competent person with a full handover;
- the standby person knows how to raise the alarm if a person inside requires emergency assistance, shall not enter the space/pit, and shall wait for the emergency response;
- the standby person monitors air quality on entry and each re-entry and keeps a log of who enters and exits;
- an approved permit to work has been obtained and, where required, supplemented by an entry certificate/checklist and any special procedures to be followed;
- JSA/TRA and TRIC/TBT requirements have been completed, and a safety meeting has been held;
- Operator/Client representatives have been informed or notified and client authorization obtained where required;
- communication systems and equipment have been tested, signalling arrangements confirmed, and radio silence applied where required;
- necessary electrical isolation, mechanical isolation, and LOTO are arranged and in place before entry, and isolations are demonstrated to the work party;
- all necessary closed valves are closed and secured, all necessary open valves are open and secured, the area is drained of liquids as much as possible, and the mud pump is switched off and locked out when the relief line is pointing into the area;
- the system is vented and gas-freed as required, and pit atmosphere testing confirms no H2S or explosive gases are present;
- no source of ignition will be introduced into the pit/space;
- correct signs, warning signs, barricades, restricted-area controls, and barriers are in place, and manhole covers are removed only when access is secured;
- the area is clean, anti-slip matting is deployed where necessary, and grounding/bonding or a water curtain is provided where required;
- an oxygen/gas detector or continuous gas monitor is on site, calibrated, and available for use;
- rescue equipment is available and in working condition, including a portable tripod with a combined fall arrestor-retriever winch or similar system;
- all entrants wear a full body harness, a full body harness is also available as a rescue means, access/egress is adequate, access ladders are in good condition, and illumination in the work area is sufficient;
- the rescue team and emergency response team (ERT) are aware of the entry, and the medic is notified where required;
- the opening is wide enough to permit a man with a SCBA (Self Contained Breather Apparatus) to enter, and if the confined space is long, fabrication and fitting of a secondary escape/rescue hatch are considered; and
- the required procedures, other precautions, and task-specific equipment/tools have been identified on the permit.

Where tools and equipment are part of the task or emergency arrangements, the permit/checklist shall identify and verify, as applicable, fire detector, fire equipment, gas detector, air movers, scaffolding, ladders, power tools, electrical tools, arc welder, cutting torch, grinder, needle gun, radios, crane, forklift, man basket, ammeter, voltmeter, multimeter, insulated tools, lighting, pressure gauge, rescue equipment, and access/egress arrangements.

For electrical hazards, portable electrical tools, including lights, with a source greater than 50 Volts are prohibited inside confined spaces because of electric shock hazard. If it is necessary to use portable tools with a source greater than 50 Volts, an isolation transformer shall be installed. Portable electrical tools, including lights, used inside confined spaces shall be operated at the lowest voltage reasonably practicable, and the electric shock hazards and mitigating measures shall be identified in the relevant JSA/risk assessment for the specific task.

Where Hot Work is also required in the confined space, the permit shall additionally confirm that the Operator's Representative has been notified; precautions have been taken against releases of gas; oil spills and other combustibles have been removed; drain openings have been plugged; combustible gas tests have been carried out and found to be nil; portable lighting requirements have been reviewed; the welding machine is in good condition, earthed, and fitted with a spark arrestor; a fire/safety guard is nominated and positioned; the required safety equipment is in place, including dry powder extinguishers, fireblankets, a continuous gas monitor, safety harness/life line, and firehose for cooling; the required PPE is available, including eye protection, breathing protection (mask), ear protection, welder's protective clothing, and welder's protective gloves; the worksite is tented, screened, or barriered as required; welding sets and other power tools are isolated when unattended; the worksite is clean and safe after completion; and the worksite is re-inspected 15 to 30 minutes after completion to assure that no smouldering fires remain.

All personnel on the rig site shall comply with all checked precautions, including third parties and Operator representatives.

**7.9.** Lifelines, body harnesses, and other rescue equipment must be provided during confined space entry. Authorized Entrants shall don a full body harness that has a mechanical lifting device attached for non-entry rescue. During permit preparation, the entry permit, JSA and/or Risk Assessment, and rescue and retrieval plan shall identify the rescue method and the protective and emergency equipment required for the specific entry.

For all work involving entry into a vessel or other confined space, the minimum protective and rescue equipment shall, as applicable, include:

- a portable multi-gas detector for gas monitoring, capable of continuously monitoring oxygen content, H2S content, and Lower Explosive Limit (LEL), complete with accessories to allow remote detection;
- safety harnesses complete with shoulder D-rings and retrieval full body harnesses, including one company-approved full body harness per entrant, one full body harness for the rescue team, a safety retrieval rope, Y-lanyard, tag lines, and self-retracting lifelines (SRLs);
- a tripod or rescue tripod complete with tripod winch, or a portable tripod with combined fall arrestor-retrieving winch or similar system, positioned at the confined space opening/entry point and, for tank or hatch entry, installed above the opening in straight alignment over the hatch;
- respiratory protective equipment, including SCBA where necessary, one 30-minute SCBA per rescue team member and, in Oman rescue plans/checklists, 1 x 30-minute SCBA per pit entrant and 30-minute SCBA for the rescue team, with some Oman checklists also stating 1 x 30-minute SCBA per rescue team leader; and one 15-minute escape set available per person involved in CSE tasks;
- casualty handling and emergency equipment, including a stretcher that allows rescue of an injured person from inside the confined space, a scoop stretcher, basket stretcher, backboard or spine backboard device, first aid kit, ambulance on standby, and 1 x MEWP and 1 x Banksman Jacket where identified in the rescue plan;
- ventilation, lighting, communications, and site controls, including an explosion-proof air exhaust fan or venturi, explosion-proof lights if required, explosion-proof radios or radios if required by risk assessment, appropriate warning signs and barricades, a standby person/man with radio, and full PPE as specified by risk assessment.

The rig shall have adequate, fit-for-purpose confined space rescue equipment that meets the requirements of ANSI standards or other equivalent standards. In Saudi Arabia operations, additional equipment and inspection detail is referenced in Drilling Safety Equipment Procedure K-KS-HS-PR-004 and Safety to Work at Height Procedure K-KS-HS-PR-032. Rescue equipment must be readily available at the confined space entry point, have proper inspection and certification, and be checked visually prior to use. The tripod winch line shall be adequately spooled/unspooled and free from knots or sticking. Stairways, walkways, access, and egress shall always be kept free from obstructions. Assistant Drillers and Derrickmen shall be designated First Aiders, and the Rig Medic or Site Medic shall be informed of confined space entry tasks and ready with all necessary first aid equipment.

Whenever work in a confined space is carried out, arrangements that are suitable and sufficient for the rescue of persons in the event of an emergency must be considered as part of the JSA and/or Risk Assessment requirements. A confined space rescue and retrieval plan shall be completed prior to any confined space entry being undertaken. It shall form the basis of discussion within the emergency contingency planning aspect of the toolbox talk, be as descriptive as possible including drawings and sketches and additional sheets as required, and a copy of this plan shall be attached to the entry permit at the entrance to the confined space entry point. At a minimum, the plan shall record the Location of Task, Rig Site/Name, Permit No., Date/Time, and the reference risk assessment/lifting plan number; list emergency numbers for the Medic, Hospital — N/A (Rig Clinic) where applicable, Immediate supervisor, and Emergency services such as fire service and ambulance; and identify the Rescue Team PIC and team positions 1, 2, and 3. The plan shall also identify highlighted risks applicable to the job, including killing gas, lack of oxygen, slipping & tripping hazard, water mud, drop object, and bad communication with rescue team, and confirm the required document and isolation package, including COW: PTW - PIP - Isolation Permit - TRIC - Checklist - WI - Rescue Plan & Valid Authorisations, Electrical Isolation (LOTO) of agitators and inside VFD for agitators (& MP if required), and Mechanical Isolation of valves (& MP if required).

Before any entry, the Rescue Team Leader shall confirm that the rescue plan and equipment requirements have been discussed and understood by all members of the rescue team. All rescue team members must be informed of their role and be competent to carry out their designated role. Before commencing confined space work, ERP personnel, including the medic, must know their role and responsibility in the event that a person is injured and requires rescue from the confined space. The ERP members are those personnel listed on the installation Station Bill, and all ERP members must be fully trained and capable of conducting a safe and fast rescue without endangering the injured person, themselves, or other crew members at the worksite. Weekly fire and evacuation drills shall periodically be used, at least every 90 days, for the purpose of exercising the ERP crew, including the medic, in the scenario of a person in need of rescue from a confined space. Because over 50% of workers who die in confined spaces are attempting to rescue other workers, rescuers must be trained in and follow established emergency procedures and use appropriate equipment and techniques such as lifelines, respiratory protection, and standby persons; rescue shall be well planned, drills shall be frequently conducted, and unplanned rescue can result in a double fatality or multiple fatalities.

The permit and rescue plan shall define the initial rescue sequence. On discovery of a downed worker, the watchman or standby person shall activate the emergency response procedure, call for help using intercom/radio or radio, wait for emergency response/assistance, and make any required PA announcement to inform the Medic or Doctor, the Toolpusher, and the client's representative. Atmospheric testing shall then be performed to check whether gas/H2S is present in the confined space; Oman rescue steps specifically require the authorized gas detector (AGT) to check gas levels for LEL, CO, O2, and H2S in the tank. Rescue team members shall put on full body harnesses, and the watchman shall explain what happened. Any rescue member entering the confined space shall don breathing apparatus before entry; one member of the rescue team may then put on a retrieval-type harness, descend into the confined space, attempt to determine the casualty's condition, relay that information to the rescue team leader on the spot, and wait for further instruction. The tripod shall be erected on top of the opening or open hatch, the Y-lanyard connected to the tripod winch line, and the tripod winch line lowered inside the confined space. The rescuer shall attach the Y-lanyard to the casualty's retrieval harness and secure it; if further rescue equipment is needed, it shall be supplied to the rescuer. On signal, personnel outside the confined space shall lift the tripod winch line carefully while the rescuer guides the casualty's body out. A stretcher shall be ready outside the confined space, and the casualty shall be placed on it once rescued; where spinal injuries are suspected, the casualty may first be secured on a spine backboard device before being laid into the basket. Rescue shall be completed within 10 minutes or as soon as possible.

Where H2S is detected, the rescue team members shall don SCBAs, enter the space using SRLs from the subbase or tripod winch, move the casualty under the rescue tripod, connect the rescue tripod winch with SRL to the injured person's full body harness, raise the person out of the tank, place and secure the person in the stretcher, carry the person to the upwind Muster Point, and have the medic assess the patient, provide necessary first aid, prepare the patient for medevac, and transfer the patient to the ambulance stretcher. The ambulance driver shall then transport the victim to the nearest clinic or hospital according to the rig's location, with stretcher securement and transfer arrangements addressed in the rescue plan.

For Oman vertical-entry vessel operations, the rescue tripod shall be ready for use and located close to the entry/exit point. H&P's global requirement remains that entrants wear a full body harness fitted for non-entry rescue; however, in this regional variant the rescue line is attached to the person's safety harness only while descending into the confined space or climbing back out, and is not left attached during the work phase because continuous attachment may introduce slip, caught, or entanglement hazards and is not an effective means of recovery except where the tripod/line is being used for a vertical lift.
